Sales Prediction for Big Mart Outlets¶

The data scientists at BigMart have collected 2013 sales data for 1559 products across 10 stores in different cities. Also, certain attributes of each product and store have been defined. The aim is to build a predictive model and predict the sales of each product at a particular outlet. Using this model, BigMart will try to understand the properties of products and outlets which play a key role in increasing sales.

Dealing with Missing Values¶

We observe missing values in the columns : Item_Weight and Outlet_Size . Also , Item_Visibility consists of a good chunk of Zeros 's , which seems impractical , because no Mart would be willing to have any of their Item_Visbility equal to zeros

We shall be dealing with these 3 columns in the following order :

1 ) Item_Weight

2 ) Outlet_Size

3 ) Item_Visibility

Until now , I am unable to find a foolproof method in order to fill Item_Weight . But we still have one more attribute to help us out and that is Item_Identifier

Also , Item_Identifier might turn out as the strongest attribute when it comes to filling Item_Weight . Because , Item_Identifier is specific to each unique type of item . For example ,looking up against just Item_Type , might lead to wrong assumptions because an apple and a watermelon dont share the same weight. While ,on the other side of the coin , Item Identifier ' FDD08 ' might mean apple , that tends to share similar weight with other apples that eventually have the same Item_Idntifier

Until now , there are 2 possibilites :

1 ) Treat Missing Outlet_Size as a different categorical variable all together , because it has unique outlets

2 ) Treat Missing Outlet_Size by taking mode with respect to each Outlet_Type(indirectly , treat them as 'Small' because Small dominates in each and every Outlet_Size)

Alright ! . Now that we know how to fill these zeros in Item_Visibility , I have a small plan :

1 ) Create a copy of original datafile . ( Helping_datafile )

2 ) Treat Supermarket Type1 / Type2 / Type3 , as Supermarket ONLY , since they posses the same Item_Visibility mean

3 ) Extract 2 datafiles from here , a ) only_supermarket_datafile , b ) only_grocery_datafile

4 ) Change 0 to NaN in both , since while taking the mean , it wont consider that particular value which is equivalent to NaN

And finally fill null values(intially , that we called as zero ) with the help of Item_Identifier

Feature Engineering¶

First things first . We notice that Item_Identifier carries some really significant information within its name . And that is . . .

The first 2 letters of each Item_Identifier signifies , the following :

DR that stands for Drinks

FD that stands for Foods

Nc that stands for Non Consumables

row=[]
def get_models(X_train_dataset,y_train_dataset,X_test_dataset):
    for i in features_list:
        for j in models_list:
            if j=='Linear':
                X_train_dataset=X_train_dataset[i]
                X_test_dataset=X_test_dataset[i]
                linreg=LinearRegression()
                linreg.fit(X_train_dataset , y_train_dataset)
                linreg_y_pred = linreg.predict(X_test_dataset)
                row.append([i , j ,np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test,linreg_y_pred))])
                X_train_dataset=X_train_temporary
                y_train_dataset=y_train_temporary
                X_test_dataset=X_test_temporary
            elif j=='Decision Tree':
                X_train_dataset=X_train_dataset[i]
                X_test_dataset=X_test_dataset[i]
                dtr = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=31)
                dtr.fit(X_train_dataset,y_train_dataset)
                dtr_y_pred = dtr.predict(X_test_dataset)
                row.append([i , j ,np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test,dtr_y_pred))])
                X_train_dataset=X_train_temporary
                y_train_dataset=y_train_temporary
                X_test_dataset=X_test_temporary
            elif j=='Random Forest':
                X_train_dataset=X_train_dataset[i]

learning_rates = [1, 0.5, 0.25, 0.1, 0.05, 0.01]
train_results = []
test_results = []
for eta in learning_rates:
    model = GradientBoostingRegressor(learning_rate=eta,random_state=0)
    model.fit(tempX_train, y_train)
    train_pred = model.predict(tempX_train)
    error1= np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_train,train_pred))
    train_results.append(error1)
    y_pred = model.predict(tempX_test)
    error2= np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test,y_pred))
    test_results.append(error2)
from matplotlib.legend_handler import HandlerLine2D
line1, = plt.plot(learning_rates, train_results, 'b', label='Train Error')
line2, = plt.plot(learning_rates, test_results, 'r', label='Test Error')
plt.legend(handler_map={line1: HandlerLine2D(numpoints=2)})
plt.ylabel('Error')
plt.xlabel('learning rate')
plt.show()

min_samples_leaf : - Training vs Testing Error

In [169]:
min_samples_leafs = np.linspace(0.1, 0.5, 5, endpoint=True)
train_results = []
test_results = []
for min_samples_leaf in min_samples_leafs:
    model = GradientBoostingRegressor(min_samples_leaf=min_samples_leaf,random_state=0)
    model.fit(tempX_train, y_train)
    train_pred = model.predict(tempX_train)
    error1= np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_train,train_pred))
    train_results.append(error1)
    y_pred = model.predict(tempX_test)
    error2= np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test,y_pred))
    test_results.append(error2)
from matplotlib.legend_handler import HandlerLine2D
line1, = plt.plot(min_samples_leafs, train_results, 'b', label='Train Error')
line2, = plt.plot(min_samples_leafs, test_results, 'r', label='Test Error')
plt.legend(handler_map={line1: HandlerLine2D(numpoints=2)})
plt.ylabel('Error')
plt.xlabel('Min_Samples_Leaf')
plt.show()
